c. Produce a nice table indicating, for each year, which party won the Candidate vote and which party won the Party vote.

library(tidyr)

nzge_c <- nzge %>%
  group_by(election_year, voting_type, party) %>%
  summarise(total_votes = sum(votes, na.rm = TRUE), .groups = "drop") %>%
  group_by(election_year, voting_type) %>%
  slice_max(total_votes, with_ties = FALSE) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  pivot_wider(
    names_from = voting_type,
    values_from = party,
    names_glue = "{voting_type}_winner"
  ) %>%
  arrange(election_year)

d. Identify the player(s) with the highest win-rate. (Note that this is NOT asking for the highest number of wins.) Restrict to players with at least 5 matches.

wins <- tennis %>% count(winner_name, name = "wins")

plays <- tennis %>% mutate(player = winner_name) %>%
  bind_rows(tennis %>% mutate(player=loser_name)) %>%
  count(player, name = "matches")

win_rate <- wins %>% rename(player = winner_name) %>%
  inner_join(plays, by ="player") %>% filter(matches>= 5) %>% 
  mutate(win_rate=wins/matches) %>% arrange(desc(win_rate))

For each of the following, produce a publication-ready plot which addresses the question. Use your plot to support an argument for your question.

a. How many major and minor spikes in cases were there?

library(zoo)

Attaching package: 'zoo'
The following objects are masked from 'package:base':

    as.Date, as.Date.numeric
library(ggplot2)

covid <- covid %>% mutate(date = as.Date(date))

covid_a <- covid %>% group_by(date) %>% summarise(cases=sum(cases), .groups = "drop") %>%
  arrange(date)

covid_a <- covid_a %>% mutate(base_mean = rollmean(cases, k = 7, fill = NA, align = "center"),
    base_sd= rollapply(cases, width = 7, sd, fill = NA, align = "center")) %>% mutate(z = (cases - base_mean) / base_sd) 

covid_a <- covid_a %>% mutate(class=case_when(z >= 2~"major",z >= 1~"minor",TRUE ~ "none")) 

major_spikes <- covid_a %>% filter(class == "major")
minor_spikes <- covid_a %>% filter(class == "minor")

cat("Number of major spikes:", nrow(major_spikes), "\n")
Number of major spikes: 7 
cat("Number of minor spikes:", nrow(minor_spikes), "\n")
Number of minor spikes: 148

I standardized COVID case counts using a 7-day rolling mean and standard deviation to calculate a local z-score for each date. A major spike was defined as a day when cases exceeded the 7-day baseline by at least two standard deviations (z â¥ 2), while a minor spike was defined as one to two standard deviations above baseline (1 â¤ z < 2). It is shown that there are 7 major spikes and 148 minor spikes.

ggplot(covid_a, aes(x = date, y = cases)) + geom_line(color = "gray40", linewidth = 0.5) +
  geom_point(data = major_spikes, aes(x = date, y = cases),
             color = "red", size = 3, shape = 17) +
  geom_point(data = minor_spikes, aes(x = date, y = cases),color = "blue", size = 2, shape = 16) +labs(title = "National Daily COVID-19 Cases with Identified Spikes",
    subtitle = "Red triangles = major spikes,  Blue points = minor spikes",
    x = "Date",y = "Daily Cases") + theme_minimal()
